SIMPLE: welk
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Welk
<hw>Welk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Welked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Welking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>welken</ets>; cf. D. &
G. <ets>welken</ets> to wither, G. <ets>welk</ets> withered, OHG.
<ets>welc</ets> moist. See <er>Welkin</er>, and cf.
<er>Wilt</er>.]</ety> <def>To wither; to fade; also, to decay; to
decline; to wane.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When ruddy Phoebus 'gins to <qex>welk</qex> in west.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The church, that before by insensible degrees <qex>welked</qex>
and impaired, now with large steps went down hill decaying.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Welk
<hw>Welk</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to wither; to wilt.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mot thy <qex>welked</qex> neck be to-broke [broken].</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To contract; to shorten.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now sad winter <qex>welked</qex> hath the day.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To soak; also, to beat severely.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Welk
<hw>Welk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A pustule. See 2d
<er>Whelk</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Welk
<hw>Welk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A whelk.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welked</ent>⟦br⟧
